Yash PratapYash Pratap • YouVerified • You Web Dev, System Design, AIWeb Dev, System Design, AI 5d • Edited • 5 days ago • Edited • Visible to anyone on or off LinkedIn
You can’t make the hashtag#Taliban accountable without democracy.

Moral policing by Indian female journalists can’t suddenly grant the women of Afghanistan their rights.

First, Sharia Law has to go.

It served a purpose over a thousand years ago — it introduced the idea of universal education, laid the foundations for banking and contract systems, and gave daughters the right to property, effectively ending practices that resembled witch-hunting (for example, Sati and dowry deaths in India) around the world.

But we can’t stay stuck there.

Sharia and the Quran are not the same, just as the Manusmriti and the Gita are not the same.

Even from an academic perspective, a religious text should be free from a single human alteration so it can assert its claim as ‘The Word of God.’

I'm bit surprised by a paradox.

Religious scriptures can't be translated without science (no word, no symbol) which means they can't be understood without science also so we are okay with using Science to reach the point "What is written"

But we can't question the meaning of that written document inside using Science.

In simple words we are okay with using science to decode the meaning of each word but when we combine these words to make sentences then we suddenly drop science to decode meaning of sentences and accept the popular narrative.

Why such double standards ?

Yash Pratap Justice, unfortunately, is not always served, even in democratic societies. War criminals and rapists may be elected and celebrated, while the innocent who raise their voice are imprisoned or tortured to death. We see this all too often.

So what about those instances where wrongdoers go unpunished and justice remains unfulfilled in this world? From a secular/atheistic perspective, death marks the end and we become nothing more than decayed matter. In contrast, from a theistic/objective morality perspective, the concept of afterlife offers ultimate justice for both those who received justice in this world and those who did not. In this system, every person’s actions carry their due weight, regardless of status. God’s judgment embodies perfect justice and mercy, considering the nuances of each individual’s life, intentions, and actions.

Faiza Fayaz Sait Okay I understood what you're asking and I wasn't able to articulate it properly.

If we translate the religious scriptures from original source using science and we consider science as objective then only we can claim the translation we did was objective.

To test if anything is objective or not we need to use science.

I'm not saying science is totally objective because there is a famous problem of Induction by David Hume which we're not able to solve yet, it tells us whatever we know, it's only because of "inductive reasoning" so it's impossible to have any absolute proof of anything in the world you understand using science but it doesn't mean that the religious scriptures which we translate using science is absolute also.

This is very well known problem of philosophy of science.

Himanshu S. After the Battle of Talas in 751, when the Arabs captured Chinese prisoners and learned the technique of mass paper production, they combined this new knowledge with the mathematical works of Aryabhata and Brahmagupta—because contracts, currency, and accounting all require precise numerical systems. This fusion laid the foundation for the sakk, regarded as the world’s first banking instrument. To support this system, Islamic Sharia Law introduced several groundbreaking reforms: universal access to education, property rights for daughters (absent in all religions like Hindu Christian etc), and protections that curtailed practices like the witch-hunting of women.

Real history is very strange.

Real history is not Mythology or some politically motivated story.

History of Technology reveal more truth about our civilization than any politically motivated conventional history.
